=====Usage notes=====
The inflected forms {{m|en|bade}}, {{m|en|bad}}, and {{m|en|bidden}} are archaic. They remain in marginal use, particularly in greetings, as in “bade farewell”, but uninflected ''bid'' is significantly more common, and {{m|en||bidden}} is especially rare.<ref>“[http://grammarist.com/usage/bid-bade-bidden/ Bid, bade, bidden]”, ''Grammarist''</ref>

When ''bidden'' does occur, it is usually in an elevated, ironical, or metaphorical style, e.g "I have ''bidden'' farewell to my prospects of promotion."

When ''bade'' (spelled ''bad'' so rarely that this variant is not mentioned in most dictionaries) is used in formal speech, the pronunciation {{IPAchar|/bæd/}} may be heard. However, when a dated text with the spelling ''bade'' is read aloud or recited (e.g. on stage, in school, or in church etc.) the [[spelling pronunciation]] {{IPAchar|/beɪd/}} is quite usual.

